  "sections": {
    "Background": {
      "text": "Unicellular spore-forming parasitic\nprotozoa\nthat are found pervasively throughout the environment.\n[1]\nMicrosporidiosis most commonly affects immunosuppressed individuals and seldom has implications for the immunocompetent patient.",
      "subsections": {},
      "tables": [],
      "links": [
        {
          "text": "protozoa",
          "url": "https://wikem.org/wiki/Protozoa"
        }
      ]
    },
    "Clinical_Features": {
      "text": "Clinical manifestations are wide ranging and typically affect immunosuppressed hosts (e.g. HIV/AIDS, long-term steroid use, transplant and chemotherapy patients), travelers, children, and the elderly\n[2]\n. The most common manifestation is copious\ndiarrhea\nwith volume depletion leading to\nelectrolyte derangements\n.\n[3]",
      "subsections": {
        "Immunosuppressed_patients:": {
          "text": "Profuse watery\ndiarrhea\nwith massive fluid loss\nCholangitis\nand\nacalculous cholecystitis\nDisseminated infection\nMyositis",
          "tables": []
        },
        "Immunocompetent_patients:": {
